Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults".

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

Either HTTP or HTTPS. coreUsername - The username for the NAS core. corePassword - The password for the NAS user. id - The ID of the object to process. Responses\: success - The operation completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. Returns\: commandStatus - The status of the NAS command. text - The response text of the NAS command. stackTrace - The stack trace (If any) of the NAS command. returnResult - Result of NAS diagnostic run 3dabe787-9998-4143-8e84-26372b5b301a.a2770d05-a7fe-41a6-aded-0aad02c40cb7.description=Iterates through a list of values. If the list changes while running, the updates will be appended to the list. Inputs\: list - The list to iterate through. separator - A delimiter that separates elements in the list. Returns\: The current element of the list, if the response is has more Responses\: has more - Another value was in the list, and has been returned. has no more - The iterator has gone fully through the list. This response will only be returned once per iteration through the list, a subsequent call to the Iterator will restart the Iteration through the list. failure - failed to process the list. Note\: Where the iterator is in the list is tracked by each step's unique id. Therefore you can iterate on the same list from multiple steps simultaneously. WARNING\: Any step that will use the results of this Iterator operation will, by default, attempt to assign that step's inputs from a flow variable. If this is left checked, then the first element of the iterator will be used for every cycle of iteration.. 3dabe787-9998-4143-8e84-26372b5b301a.b032d79b-4b71-48be-8fda-e128492f7875.prompt=Enter a value for coreUsername 3dabe787-9998-4143-8e84-26372b5b301a.b3b3e60b-06eb-4716-a109-3296568928a8.description=
Generates a readable report from a set of lists. The lists MUST have a 1-to-1 correspondence (The same number of elements in all lists). Add an input for each list you wish to process.

Inputs\:
format - The format to generate the report in. Valid option is plain, if not specified plain is used. This input is a placeholder so that additional formats can be added in the future.
delimiter - The delimiter used to separate elements in the lists.

Responses\:
success - The operation completed Successfully.
failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
The generated report.
3dabe787-9998-4143-8e84-26372b5b301a.cad2002a-aa51-4d04-be87-2802463966dc.prompt=NA Diagnostic\: 3dabe787-9998-4143-8e84-26372b5b301a.d5f842e6-119b-4a5e-9aee-645e445069bc.description=Runs a diagnostic task against a device or device group. Works similar to "Schedule Task" Inputs\: coreHost - The DNS name or IP Address of your NAS core. corePort - The port to connect to your NAS core on. coreProtocol - The protocol to connect to your NAS core with. Either HTTP or HTTPS. coreUsername - The username for the NAS core. corePassword - The password for the NAS user. id - The ID of the object to process. diagnosticName - A diagnostic to run. Built-in diagnostics are 'NAS Routing Table', 'NAS Interfaces' and 'NAS OSPF Neighbors' among others. See the NAS diagnostics selection list. ip - The IP address of the network device. groupName - The group name of a list of networked devices. comment - The comment to tie to this action. repeat - (\#min | \#\:\# | \#days | \#weeks | \#months) where \# is a positive integer. \#\:\# is hours\:minutes--the two integers do not have to be the same. Do not use this option with -sync. startDate - Date of the start of the task (YYYY\:MM\:DD\:HH\:mm) returnImmediately - A boolean value. If true, the operation will return once the task is scheduled. If false the operation will wait for the task to complete before returning. Responses\: success - The operation completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. Returns\: commandStatus - The status of the NAS command. text - The response text of the NAS command. stackTrace - The stack trace (If any) of the NAS command. returnResult - Text result of NAS diagnostic 3dabe787-9998-4143-8e84-26372b5b301a.description=
Perform a diagnostic on a list of network devices.

Inputs\:
coreHost - The DNS name or IP Address of your NAS core.
coreUsername - The username for the NA core.
corePassword - The password for the NA user.
deviceIPs - The comma-separated list of network device IPs to run a diagnostic on.
diagnosticName - name of diagnostic to run on them. This is any valid diagnostic name in NA.
waitTime - The time to wait for diagnostic tasks to complete (in seconds).
groupName - The group name of a list of networked devices.
startDate - Date of the start of the task. May be in one of the following formats\:  YYYY\:MM\:DD\:HH\:MM e.g. 2002\:09\:06\:12\:30, now or tomorrow.
repeat - (\#min | \#\:\# | \#days | \#weeks | \#months) where \# is a positive integer. \#\:\# is hours\:minutes--the two integers do not have to be the same.
comment - The comment to tie to this action.


Responses\:
success - The operation succeeded.
failure - The operation failed to complete.

Returns\:
returnResult - The diagnostics report on the devices.
